(534, 1, '2015-07-08 08:47:27', '2015-07-08 08:47:27', 'The Water Labyrinth is an interactive water sculpture created exclusively for Forrest Place by internationally renowned artist Jeppe Hein. The Water Labyrinth uses storm water harvested and recycled from Forrest Place and runs daily from 8am to 8pm unless Forrest Place is being used for events. Kids can cool off in the display and delight in running through the fountains, whilst parents can watch and relax at one the surrounding cafes or beanbags.', 'The Water Labyrinth', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'the-water-labyrinth', '', '', '2015-07-15 05:11:50', '2015-07-15 05:11:50', '', 0, 'http://111.93.163.213/Helloperth/php/?post_type=directories&#038;p=534', 0, 'directories', '', 0),
(535, 1, '2015-07-08 08:49:35', '2015-07-08 08:49:35', 'The island over which the causeway runs is thought to have been named after a crew member sailing with the French navigator-explorer, Captain Hamelin, in 1801. Today, Heirisson Island is the home to a colony of Western Grey Kangaroos, which can be seen in the enclosed southern part of the island. The statue of Nyoongar leader Yagan is also located on the island, which was a significant hunting ground for indigenous people. Yagan was a Noongar leader and resistance fighter during the early years of the Swan River Colony. Heirisson Island is roughly a 10-15 minute walk from the city centre.', 'Heirisson Island', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'heirisson-island', '', '', '2015-07-08 08:49:35', '2015-07-08 08:49:35', '', 0, 'http://111.93.163.213/Helloperth/php/?post_type=directories&#038;p=535', 0, 'directories', '', 0),
