(795, 1, '2015-07-16 07:29:24', '2015-07-16 07:29:24', '<a href="https://maps.google.com/maps/ms?msid=200103880838059412952.0004e9754c9f06f9114b6&amp;msa=0" target="_blank"><img class="alignright wp-image-794 size-full" src="http://111.93.163.213/Helloperth/php/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/Map-perth-transport-guide.jpg" alt="Map-perth-transport-guide" width="289" height="334" /></a>\n\n\n\n<strong>Bus and Train:</strong> Perth’s public transport system, Transperth, brings places of interest within easy reach. Visitors can make good use of buses, trains and ferries to explore Perth and Fremantle. Transperth ticket prices are determined by how far you travel. Train and ferry fares must be purchased prior to travel at the Ticket Vending Machines while bus fares can be paid as you board. Tickets are valid for up to two hours and can be used on the entire public transport system. A DayRider ticket can be purchased for daily unlimited travel with Transperth. Visit the Transperth InfoCentre at the Perth Train Station, phone 13 62 13 or visit <a href="http://www.transperth.wa.gov.au/" target="_blank">transperth.wa.gov.au</a> for more information on timetables for trains, buses, ferries and CAT buses. There’s also numerous maps, fare information and language interpretation.<!--more-->\n\n<strong>Free CAT Bus:</strong> Perth offers a free bus service that operates around the Central Business District. Buses arrive every five to ten minutes depending on the route, time of day and day of the week. Red, Green, Blue and Yellow CAT (Central Area Transit) buses operate with the routes marked on the CAT map. Fremantle also offers a free blue and red CAT bus service, which operates seven days a week. For more information visit the Transperth InfoCentres, phone 13 62 13 or visit <a href="http://www.transperth.wa.gov.au/UsingTransperth/Highfrequencybusservices.aspx" target="_blank">transperth.wa.gov.au. </a>\n\nTaxis can be flagged down in the street or there are numerous taxi ranks around the city. Friday and Saturday nights can be very busy and long queues and waiting periods are common. Taxis can also be booked in advance by calling: <strong>Swan Taxis - 13 13 30 or </strong><strong>Black &amp; White Cabs - 13 10 08</strong>\n\n<p style="text-align: right;">View <a href="https://maps.google.com/maps/ms?msid=200103880838059412952.0004e9754c9f06f9114b6&amp;msa=0" target="_blank">Perth Transport Guide Map</a> in a larger map</p>\n\n<strong>Ferries</strong> are a pleasant alternative to getting around where you can enjoy the views and calm waters along the beautiful Swan River. From Barrack Square, Transperth run a regular ferry across the river to South Perth, <a href="http://www.transperth.wa.gov.au" target="_blank">www.transperth.wa.gov.au </a>or Captain Cook Cruises <a href="http://www.captaincookcruises.com.au" target="_blank">www.captaincookcruises.com.au</a> offer direct routes to Fremantle and the Swan Valley.\n\nSee below for a good selection of car hire companies who offer every type of vehicle from small cars, family wagons to campervans and four wheel drives. If you’re planning on travelling independently and hiring a car, WA is teeming with awe-inspiring scenic drives that will take your breath away. Roads are wide and easy to drive, and WA observes the same driving rules as the rest of Australia. Vehicles travel on the left hand side of the road and wearing seatbelts is compulsory for all passengers. Accidents do happen and you are much safer if you are belted up, plus you’ll receive a hefty fine if a police officer stops you! Make sure all passengers where seat belts too. For more information, visit <a href="http://www.ors.wa.gov.au/" target="_blank">www.ors.wa.gov.au</a>.', 'Transport', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '399-autosave-v1', '', '', '2015-07-16 07:29:24', '2015-07-16 07:29:24', '', 399, 'http://111.93.163.213/Helloperth/php/399-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
